 towards migration is growing rapidly and becoming increasingly complex. As the first-wave generation of migrants ages, their children and even grandchildren are reaching adulthood having spent their entire lives in the countries their families chose long ago. International Perspectives: Integration and Inclusion is a wide-ranging exploration of this new, global reality. While many countries have been, and remain, resistant to migration, the sheer volume of people moving from one country to another is forcing public policy and perceptions to change. Migrant inclusion and integration, however, remains an issue in many locales. Insightful and timely, this volume brings together contributions from various countries and levels of the migrant experience in order to consider the ways in which states can facilitate the integration and inclusion of newcomers and minorities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEmigration and immigrationxGovernment policy. 0aEmigration and immigrationxSocial aspects. 0aImmigrantsxSocial conditions. 0aSocial integration. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aBevelander, Pieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiles, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloemraad, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, Annie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Jock, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrideres, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrideres, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGorodzeisky, Anastasia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuddleston, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https:/